S2.T1.46.46.caption: Table 1 :  Liver vessel CT segmentation on 3D-IRCADb  [ 15 ]  using 3D ResUNet as baseline. Models incorporating shape and topological constraints, a mix of both, and our own approach are compared. Best results in bold, second best results underlined.

references: Throughout the encoding stage, we set the following parameters: the number of layers llitalic_l to 5555, the initial number of feature maps f0subscript0f_{0}italic_f start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to 8888 (Fig.2), psubscript\alpha_{p}italic_ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT in Eq.10 to 1111, the number of latent code feature maps to 32, the learning rate to 104superscript10410^{-4}10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 4 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, the batch size to 2222, and the number of epochs to 1000100010001000. In contrast, for the segmentation experiments, the learning rate, batch size, and number of epochs were set to 31043superscript1043\times 10^{-4}3  10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 4 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, 2, and 1500, respectively. Additionally, the distance function d()d(\cdot)italic_d (  ) was defined as the cosine distance (Eq.6). Hyper-parameter optimization was performed using Optuna [16] with 20 trials for each configuration, and optimal \lambdaitalic_ values were determined empirically as shown in Tab.1. Random data augmentation techniques including rotation, translation, flipping, and gamma correction was applied. A 5-fold cross-validation approach was used. Deep networks were implemented using PyTorch. In practice, seeds were fixed for weight initialization, data augmentation and shuffling to ensure reproducibility.

Results in Tab.1 show the performance of different models for liver vessel segmentation, assessed using various evaluation metrics including DSC (Dice Similarity Coefficient), Jacc (Jaccard score), clDSC coefficient [17] for connectivity assessment, HD (Hausdorff distance), AVD (Absolute Volume Difference), and ASSD (Average Symmetric Surface Distance). The models include ResUNet as baseline, ResUNet+shape, ResUNet+topo, ResUNet+shape+topo, and the proposed approch. Our method outperforms the other models, achieving the highest DSC, Jacc, clDSC, and ASSD scores with 54.78%percent54.7854.78\%54.78 %, 38.00%percent38.0038.00\%38.00 %, 50.34%percent50.3450.34\%50.34 %, and 4.774.774.774.77mm respectively. It delivers robust performance in clDSC assessment, positioning it as a promising topology-aware model. Further, Fig.3 illustrates the connectivity improvement reached by our approach. In particular, fine branches remain less disconnected from main vessels compared to ResUNet+topo or ResUNet+shape+topo. The performance of our approach could be improved by calibrating the hyper-parameter psuperscript\alpha^{p}italic_ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT (Eq.10), which indirectly affects the JMPE coding scheme. Furthermore, our method allows the use of a single encoder instead of multiple encoders, thus reducing memory consumption.
